The paper deals with encoding and querying GIS data using a topological model, which involves representing the data as a planar graph and maintaining information about the relationships between nodes, edges, and faces. This suggests that the paper is likely to fall under the categories of data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), databases (cs.DB), graph theory (cs.GR), and information theory (cs.IT). Among these, cs.DS and cs.CG are the most likely categories, as they deal directly with the representation and manipulation of graphs and geometric data.
